events.description: Germanicus celebrates a triumph in Rome for his victories over the Cherusci, Chatti, and other German tribes west of the Elbe.
events.html: • 17 – Germanicus celebrates a triumph in Rome for his victories over the Cherusci, Chatti, and other German tribes west of the Elbe.[1]

events.description: Battle of Avarayr between Armenian rebels and the Sasanian Empire takes place. The Sasanids defeat the Armenians militarily but guarantee them freedom to openly practice Christianity.
events.html: • 451 – Battle of Avarayr between Armenian rebels and the Sasanian Empire takes place. The Sasanids defeat the Armenians militarily but guarantee them freedom to openly practice Christianity.[2]

events.description: England is left temporarily without a monarch after the death of King Edmund I in a street fight, resulting in Edmund's brother Eadred assuming the throne for the minority of Edmund's two sons.
events.html: • 946 – England is left temporarily without a monarch after the death of King Edmund I in a street fight, resulting in Edmund's brother Eadred assuming the throne for the minority of Edmund's two sons.[3]

events.description: King Otto I elects his six-year-old son Otto II as heir apparent and co-ruler of the East Frankish Kingdom. He is crowned at Aachen, and placed under the tutelage of his grandmother Matilda.
events.html: • 961 – King Otto I elects his six-year-old son Otto II as heir apparent and co-ruler of the East Frankish Kingdom. He is crowned at Aachen, and placed under the tutelage of his grandmother Matilda.[4]

events.description: Alfonso VII of León and Castile is crowned in León Cathedral as Imperator totius Hispaniae (Emperor of all of Spain).
events.html: • 1135 – Alfonso VII of León and Castile is crowned in León Cathedral as Imperator totius Hispaniae (Emperor of all of Spain).[5]

entities.name: Alfonso VII of León and Castile

events.description: An earthquake strikes Kamakura, Kanagawa, Japan, killing about 23,000.
events.html: • 1293 – An earthquake strikes Kamakura, Kanagawa, Japan, killing about 23,000.[6]

events.description: William of Ockham, the Franciscan Minister-General Michael of Cesena, and two other Franciscan leaders secretly leave Avignon, fearing a death sentence from Pope John XXII.
events.html: • 1328 – William of Ockham, the Franciscan Minister-General Michael of Cesena, and two other Franciscan leaders secretly leave Avignon, fearing a death sentence from Pope John XXII.

events.description: Geneva expels John Calvin and his followers from the city. Calvin lives in exile in Strasbourg for the next three years.
events.html: • 1538 – Geneva expels John Calvin and his followers from the city. Calvin lives in exile in Strasbourg for the next three years.[7]

events.description: The Battle of Haarlemmermeer, a naval engagement in the Eighty Years' War.
events.html: • 1573 – The Battle of Haarlemmermeer, a naval engagement in the Eighty Years' War.[8]

events.description: Pequot War: A combined English and Mohegan force under John Mason attacks a village in Connecticut, massacring approximately 500 Pequots.
events.html: • 1637 – Pequot War: A combined English and Mohegan force under John Mason attacks a village in Connecticut, massacring approximately 500 Pequots.

events.description: Portuguese Restoration War: Portuguese and Spanish forces both claim victory in the Battle of Montijo.
events.html: • 1644 – Portuguese Restoration War: Portuguese and Spanish forces both claim victory in the Battle of Montijo.

events.description: The Battle of Ackia is fought near the present site of Tupelo, Mississippi. British and Chickasaw soldiers repel a French and Choctaw attack on the then-Chickasaw village of Ackia.
events.html: • 1736 – The Battle of Ackia is fought near the present site of Tupelo, Mississippi. British and Chickasaw soldiers repel a French and Choctaw attack on the then-Chickasaw village of Ackia.

events.description: A Great Jubilee Day held at North Stratford, Connecticut, celebrates the end of fighting in the American Revolutionary War.
events.html: • 1783 – A Great Jubilee Day held at North Stratford, Connecticut, celebrates the end of fighting in the American Revolutionary War.

events.description: Napoléon Bonaparte assumes the title of King of Italy and is crowned with the Iron Crown of Lombardy in Milan Cathedral, the gothic cathedral in Milan.
events.html: • 1805 – Napoléon Bonaparte assumes the title of King of Italy and is crowned with the Iron Crown of Lombardy in Milan Cathedral, the gothic cathedral in Milan.

events.description: Establishment of the Peloponnesian Senate by the Greek rebels.
events.html: • 1821 – Establishment of the Peloponnesian Senate by the Greek rebels.

events.description: At least 113 people die in the Grue Church fire, the biggest fire disaster in Norway's history.
events.html: • 1822 – At least 113 people die in the Grue Church fire, the biggest fire disaster in Norway's history.

events.description: Montana is organized as a United States territory.
events.html: • 1864 – Montana is organized as a United States territory.

events.description: Conclusion of the American Civil War: The Confederate General Edmund Kirby Smith, commander of the Trans-Mississippi division, is the last full general of the Confederate Army to surrender, at Galveston, Texas.
events.html: • 1865 – Conclusion of the American Civil War: The Confederate General Edmund Kirby Smith, commander of the Trans-Mississippi division, is the last full general of the Confederate Army to surrender, at Galveston, Texas.

entities.name: Conclusion of the American Civil War

events.description: Impeachment of Andrew Johnson: President Andrew Johnson is acquitted by one vote in the United States Senate.
events.html: • 1868 – Impeachment of Andrew Johnson: President Andrew Johnson is acquitted by one vote in the United States Senate.

events.description: Boston University is chartered by the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.
events.html: • 1869 – Boston University is chartered by the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.

events.description: Russia and the United Kingdom sign the Treaty of Gandamak establishing an Afghan state.
events.html: • 1879 – Russia and the United Kingdom sign the Treaty of Gandamak establishing an Afghan state.

events.description: Nicholas II is crowned as the last Tsar of Imperial Russia.
events.html: • 1896 – Nicholas II is crowned as the last Tsar of Imperial Russia.

entities.name: Coronation of Nicholas II and Alexandra Feodorovna

events.description: Charles Dow publishes the first edition of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
events.html: • 1896 – Charles Dow publishes the first edition of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.

events.description: Thousand Days' War: The Colombian Conservative Party turns the tide of war in their favor with victory against the Colombian Liberal Party in the Battle of Palonegro.
events.html: • 1900 – Thousand Days' War: The Colombian Conservative Party turns the tide of war in their favor with victory against the Colombian Liberal Party in the Battle of Palonegro.

events.description: Românul de la Pind, the longest-running newspaper by and about Aromanians until World War II, is founded.
events.html: • 1903 – Românul de la Pind, the longest-running newspaper by and about Aromanians until World War II, is founded.[9]

events.description: The first major commercial oil strike in the Middle East is made at Masjed Soleyman in southwest Persia. The rights to the resource were quickly acquired by the Anglo-Persian Oil Company.
events.html: • 1908 – The first major commercial oil strike in the Middle East is made at Masjed Soleyman in southwest Persia. The rights to the resource were quickly acquired by the Anglo-Persian Oil Company.

events.description: The Democratic Republic of Georgia is established.
events.html: • 1918 – The Democratic Republic of Georgia is established.

events.description: The first 24 Hours of Le Mans is held in France. Run annually in June thereafter, it became the oldest endurance racing event in the world.
events.html: • 1923 – The first 24 Hours of Le Mans is held in France. Run annually in June thereafter, it became the oldest endurance racing event in the world.[10]

events.description: The last Ford Model T rolls off the assembly line after a production run of 15,007,003 vehicles.
events.html: • 1927 – The last Ford Model T rolls off the assembly line after a production run of 15,007,003 vehicles.[11]

events.description: In the House of Commons of Northern Ireland, Tommy Henderson begins speaking on the Appropriation bill. By the time he sits down in the early hours of the following morning, he had spoken for ten hours.
events.html: • 1936 – In the House of Commons of Northern Ireland, Tommy Henderson begins speaking on the Appropriation bill. By the time he sits down in the early hours of the following morning, he had spoken for ten hours.

entities.name: House of Commons of Northern Ireland

events.description: Walter Reuther and members of the United Auto Workers (UAW) clash with Ford Motor Company security guards at the River Rouge Complex complex in Dearborn, Michigan, during the Battle of the Overpass.
events.html: • 1937 – Walter Reuther and members of the United Auto Workers (UAW) clash with Ford Motor Company security guards at the River Rouge Complex complex in Dearborn, Michigan, during the Battle of the Overpass.[12]

events.description: In the United States, the House Un-American Activities Committee begins its first session.
events.html: • 1938 – In the United States, the House Un-American Activities Committee begins its first session.

events.description: World War II: Operation Dynamo: In northern France, Allied forces begin a massive evacuation from Dunkirk, France. The Battle of Dunkirk begins simultaneously as Allied defenders fight to slow down the German offensive.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: Operation Dynamo: In northern France, Allied forces begin a massive evacuation from Dunkirk, France. The Battle of Dunkirk begins simultaneously as Allied defenders fight to slow down the German offensive.[13]

events.description: World War II: The Siege of Calais ends with the surrender of the British and French garrison.
events.html: • 1940 – World War II: The Siege of Calais ends with the surrender of the British and French garrison.

events.description: World War II: The Battle of Gazala begins, in present-day Libya.
events.html: • 1942 – World War II: The Battle of Gazala begins, in present-day Libya.[14]

events.description: The U.S. Congress passes Public Law 80-557, which permanently establishes the Civil Air Patrol as an auxiliary of the United States Air Force.
events.html: • 1948 – The U.S. Congress passes Public Law 80-557, which permanently establishes the Civil Air Patrol as an auxiliary of the United States Air Force.

events.description: British Guiana gains independence, becoming Guyana.
events.html: • 1966 – British Guiana gains independence, becoming Guyana.[15]

events.description: The Beatles' album Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band is released.
events.html: • 1967 – The Beatles' album Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band is released.[16]

entities.name: Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band

events.description: H-dagurinn in Iceland: Traffic changes from driving on the left to driving on the right overnight.
events.html: • 1968 – H-dagurinn in Iceland: Traffic changes from driving on the left to driving on the right overnight.[17]

events.description: Apollo program: Apollo 10 returns to Earth after a successful eight-day test of all the components needed for the forthcoming first crewed Moon landing.
events.html: • 1969 – Apollo program: Apollo 10 returns to Earth after a successful eight-day test of all the components needed for the forthcoming first crewed Moon landing.

events.description: The Soviet Tupolev Tu-144 becomes the first commercial transport to exceed Mach 2.
events.html: • 1970 – The Soviet Tupolev Tu-144 becomes the first commercial transport to exceed Mach 2.

events.description: Bangladesh Liberation War: The Pakistan Army slaughters at least 71 Hindus in Burunga, Sylhet, Bangladesh.
events.html: • 1971 – Bangladesh Liberation War: The Pakistan Army slaughters at least 71 Hindus in Burunga, Sylhet, Bangladesh.

events.description: The United States and the Soviet Union sign the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
events.html: • 1972 – The United States and the Soviet Union sign the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.

events.description: Italian Prime Minister Arnaldo Forlani and his coalition cabinet resign following a scandal over membership of the pseudo-masonic lodge P2 (Propaganda Due).
events.html: • 1981 – Italian Prime Minister Arnaldo Forlani and his coalition cabinet resign following a scandal over membership of the pseudo-masonic lodge P2 (Propaganda Due).[18]

events.description: An EA-6B Prowler crashes on the flight deck of the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz, killing 14 crewmen and injuring 45 others.
events.html: • 1981 – An EA-6B Prowler crashes on the flight deck of the aircraft carrier USS Nimitz, killing 14 crewmen and injuring 45 others.[19]

events.description: The 7.8 Mw  Sea of Japan earthquake shakes northern Honshu with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (Severe). A destructive tsunami is generated that leaves about 100 people dead.
events.html: • 1983 – The 7.8 Mw  Sea of Japan earthquake shakes northern Honshu with a maximum Mercalli intensity of VIII (Severe). A destructive tsunami is generated that leaves about 100 people dead.[20]

events.description: The European Community adopts the European flag.
events.html: • 1986 – The European Community adopts the European flag.

events.description: Zviad Gamsakhurdia becomes the first elected President of the Republic of Georgia in the post-Soviet era.
events.html: • 1991 – Zviad Gamsakhurdia becomes the first elected President of the Republic of Georgia in the post-Soviet era.

events.description: Lauda Air Flight 004 breaks apart in mid-air and crashes in the Phu Toei National Park in the Suphan Buri Province of Thailand, killing all 223 people on board.
events.html: • 1991 – Lauda Air Flight 004 breaks apart in mid-air and crashes in the Phu Toei National Park in the Suphan Buri Province of Thailand, killing all 223 people on board.[21]

events.description: The Supreme Court of the United States rules in New Jersey v. New York that Ellis Island, the historic gateway for millions of immigrants, is mainly in the state of New Jersey, not New York.
events.html: • 1998 – The Supreme Court of the United States rules in New Jersey v. New York that Ellis Island, the historic gateway for millions of immigrants, is mainly in the state of New Jersey, not New York.

entities.name: Supreme Court of the United States

events.description: The first "National Sorry Day" is held in Australia. Reconciliation events are held nationally, and attended by over a million people.
events.html: • 1998 – The first "National Sorry Day" is held in Australia. Reconciliation events are held nationally, and attended by over a million people.

events.description: A MIAT Mongolian Airlines Harbin Y-12 crashes near Erdenet, Orkhon Province, Mongolia, resulting in 28 deaths.
events.html: • 1998 – A MIAT Mongolian Airlines Harbin Y-12 crashes near Erdenet, Orkhon Province, Mongolia, resulting in 28 deaths.[22]

events.description: The tugboat Robert Y. Love collides with a support pier of Interstate 40 on the Arkansas River near Webbers Falls, Oklahoma, resulting in 14 deaths and 11 others injured.
events.html: • 2002 – The tugboat Robert Y. Love collides with a support pier of Interstate 40 on the Arkansas River near Webbers Falls, Oklahoma, resulting in 14 deaths and 11 others injured.

events.description: Ukrainian-Mediterranean Airlines Flight 4230 crashes in the Turkish town of Maçka, killing 75.
events.html: • 2003 – Ukrainian-Mediterranean Airlines Flight 4230 crashes in the Turkish town of Maçka, killing 75.[23]

events.description: Severe flooding begins in eastern and southern China that will ultimately cause 148 deaths and force the evacuation of 1.3 million.
events.html: • 2008 – Severe flooding begins in eastern and southern China that will ultimately cause 148 deaths and force the evacuation of 1.3 million.

events.description: Protests triggered by the murder of George Floyd erupt in Minneapolis–Saint Paul, later becoming widespread across the United States and around the world.
events.html: • 2020 – Protests triggered by the murder of George Floyd erupt in Minneapolis–Saint Paul, later becoming widespread across the United States and around the world.[24]
